{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1039"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1039"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.33,0.4,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45062"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the Endocrine Clinic with a recent diagnosis of primary hyperparathyroidism, following an incidental finding of elevated serum calcium on a routine blood test. She is asymptomatic. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 30 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. She is planned for a minimally invasive parathyroidectomy following identification and localisation of the parathyroid adenoma preoperatively.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a generally accepted indication for surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age over 50 years","BMI over 30 kg/m2","Serum calcium greater than 2.7 mmol/L on two separate occasions","Bone density T-score less than -2.5","Parathyroid hormone level greater than 10 pmol/L"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn highly resourced healthcare settings where patients are routinely screened, patients with primary hyperparathyroidism typically present with moderate hypercalcaemia and non-suppressed to high PTH levels. Up to 85% of cases result from a single parathyroid adenoma. Complications of the disease include renal calculi, peptic ulceration, acute pancreatitis, and fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgery in patients with primary hyperparathyroidism aims to treat symptoms or prevent complications. The accepted indications for surgery include symptomatic patients, age less than 50 years, \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoporosis (T-score less than -2.5)\u003C/strong\u003E, creatinine clearance less than 60 mL/min, hypercalciuria greater than 10 mmol/day, hypercalcaemia greater than 2.85 mmol/L, and patients for whom medical surveillance is not possible, as these patients are at high risk of developing complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the following are not in themselves indications for surgery: \u003Cstrong\u003Eage over 50 years\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EBMI over 30 kg/m2\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum calcium greater than 2.7 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparathyroid hormone level greater than 10 pmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Osteoporosis is an important indicator for surgery in cases of primary hyperparathyroidism.","Surgery in primary hyperparathyroidism aims to treat symptoms or prevent complications."],"references":["Blackburn M. Primary hyperparathyroidism and familial hyperparathyroid syndromes. Aust Fam Physician. 2007;36(12). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18075629/","Insogna K. Primary Hyperparathyroidism. NEJM. 2018;379(11):1050-1059. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1714213","Bilezikian JP, Brandi ML, Eastell R, Silverberg SJ, Udelsman R, Marcocci C, Potts JT Jr. Guidelines for the management of asymptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism: summary statement from the Fourth International Workshop. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2014 Oct;99(10):3561-9. doi: 10.1210/jc.2014-1413. Epub 2014 Aug 27. PMID: 25162665; PMCID: PMC5393490."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1039"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-24T06:45:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-03T17:56:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1039"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47495"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"